2f01"},{"_type":"span","marks":["661a148170d8"],"text":"ice sheet","_key":"b301ba1fe69d"},{"text":" above it is roughly 2,700-meters (9,000-feet) thick. This ","_key":"f59193f24b70","_type":"span","marks":[]},{"text":"elevation","_key":"bcb210b46cab","_type":"span","marks":["72be0f92081d"]},{"_type":"span","marks":[],"text":" makes the South Pole much colder than the North Pole, which sits in the middle of the Arctic Ocean. In fact, the warmest ","_key":"c2e7ba1b4d1b"},{"_type":"span","marks":["52b68bfca7d5"],"text":"temperature","_key":"415fe0985f48"},{"marks":[],"text":" ever recorded at the South Pole was a freezing -12.3 degrees Celsius (9.9 degrees Fahrenheit).\n\nThe South Pole is close to the coldest place on Earth. The coldest temperature recorded at the South Pole, -82.8 degrees Celsius (-117.0 degrees Fahrenheit), is still warmer than the coldest temperature ever recorded, -89.2 degrees Celsius (-128.6 degrees Fahrenheit). That temperature was recorded at the Russian Vostok ","_key":"16a04f727be5","_type":"span"},{"_type":"span","marks":["1051c6b05b40"],"text":"Research Station","_key":"02be1337fb19"},{"marks":[],"text":", about 1,300 kilometers (808 miles) away.\n\nBecause Earth rotates on a tilted axis as it revolves around the sun, sunlight is experienced in extremes at the poles. In fact, the South Pole experiences only one sunrise (at the September ","_key":"72677f47fd4b","_type":"span"},{"_type":"span","marks":["01fe290a8013"],"text":"equinox","_key":"ccaf9889216c"},{"marks":[],"text":") and one sunset (at the March equinox) every year. From the South Pole, the sun is always above the ","_key":"c037bd6dee49","_type":"span"},{"_type":"span","marks":["17a6db9c87c1"],"text":"horizon","_key":"aa6ca6ce01cd"},{"_type":"span","marks":[],"text":" in the summer and below the horizon in the winter. This means the region experiences up to 24 hours of sunlight in the summer and 24 hours of darkness in the winter.\n\nDue to ","_key":"3e9f09696889"},{"_type":"span","marks":["bd3132afb008"],"text":"plate tectonics","_key":"98e00026ca2f"},{"_type":"span","marks":[],"text":", the exact location of the South Pole is constantly moving. Plate tectonics is the process of large slabs of Earth's ","_key":"ad0f5dcc47bc"},{"_type":"span","marks":["1e55751439b3"],"text":"crust","_key":"06b1cacd5924"},{"_type":"span","marks":[],"text":" moving slowly around the planet, bumping into and pulling apart from one another.\n\nOver billions of years, Earth's continents have shifted together and drifted apart. Millions of years ago, land that today is the east coast of South America was at the South Pole. Today, the ice sheet above the South Pole drifts about 10 meters (33 feet) every year.\n\n","_key":"78e5770999bd"},{"_type":"span","marks":["strong"],"text":"Amundsen–Scott South Pole Station\n","_key":"2321ac24d5361"},{"_type":"span","marks":[],"text":"\nCompared to the North Pole, the South Pole is relatively easy to travel to and study. The North Pole is in the middle of the Arctic Ocean, while the South Pole is on a stable piece of land.\n\nThe United States has had scientists working at Amundsen–Scott South Pole Station since 1956. Between 50 and 200 scientists and support staff live at the this research station at any given time. The station itself does not sit on the ground or ice sheet. It is able to adjust its elevation, to prevent it from being buried in snow, which ","_key":"7d388b311b90"},{"_type":"span","marks":["6957b3b4ce27"],"text":"accumulates","_key":"18c89442620d"},{"text":" at a rate of about 20 centimeters (eight inches) every year, and does not melt.\n\nIn the winter, the Amundsen–Scott South Pole Station is completely ","_key":"94f8f6e811b7","_type":"span","marks":[]},{"_type":"span","marks":["9d5b0d51402a"],"text":"self-sufficient","_key":"272525fbfec2"},{"text":". The dark sky, freezing temperatures, and ","_key":"59aff03ecc86","_type":"span","marks":[]},{"_type":"span","marks":["979d6988cb43"],"text":"gale","_key":"7d7357b38f80"},{"_type":"span","marks":[],"text":"-force winds prevent most supplies from being flown or trekked in. All food, medical supplies, and other material must be secured before the long Antarctic winter. The station's energy is provided by three enormous ","_key":"f80aa04b8b12"},{"_type":"span","marks":["62fbd57f6dbe"],"text":"generators","_key":"94bca7a10e15"},{"_type":"span","marks":[],"text":" that run on jet fuel.\n\nIn winter, stores of food are supplemented by the Amundsen–Scott South Pole Station's greenhouse. Vegetables in the greenhouse are grown with ","_key":"c873ee16c868"},{"_key":"0f167adc1331","_type":"span","marks":["791bfaec3c21"],"text":"hydroponics"},{"_key":"ff3adac884a5","_type":"span","marks":[],"text":", in a nutrient solution instead of soil.\n\nSome of the earliest discoveries made at South Pole research stations helped support the theory of "},{"_key":"97f810b1e60a","_type":"span","marks":["031818379ac5"],"text":"continental drift"},{"_type":"span","marks":[],"text":", the idea that continents drift apart and shift together. Rock samples collected near the South Pole and throughout Antarctica match samples dated to the same time period collected at ","_key":"8ad4b7660525"},{"_key":"382582cc908c","_type":"span","marks":["1e7a5f770cd8"],"text":"tropical"},{"_key":"47f9741787f7","_type":"span","marks":[],"text":" latitudes. "},{"_key":"c03063ac41cc","_type":"span","marks":["29bf4f43f432"],"text":"Geologists"},{"_type":"span","marks":[],"text":" conclude that the samples formed at the same time and the same place, and were torn apart over millions of years, as the planet split into different continents.\n\nToday, the Amundsen–Scott South Pole Station is host to a wide variety of research. The relatively undisturbed ice sheet maintains a ","_key":"ae4170f69d18"},{"_type":"span","marks":["be7cd98ae049"],"text":"pristine","_key":"e50f4c667e38"},{"_type":"span","marks":[],"text":" record of snowfalls, air quality, and ","_key":"41615eadf17a"}