 tent, equipment, and supplies for Scott, as well as a note for the King of Norway to be delivered if the ","_key":"6b01a98a59a315"},{"_key":"013e6fbb88791","_type":"span","marks":["em"],"text":"Fram"},{"marks":[],"text":" expedition failed to make it back.\n\nDisheartened, Scott's team slowly headed back north. They faced colder temperatures and harsher weather than Amundsen's team. They had fewer supplies. Suffering from hunger, ","_key":"8e52a0023cc8","_type":"span"},{"_key":"30161ba775a2","_type":"span","marks":["25abc1421406"],"text":"hypothermia"},{"_type":"span","marks":[],"text":", and ","_key":"bd432cee954c"},{"_type":"span","marks":["9a2a88577d62"],"text":"frostbite","_key":"52bfe75fe928"},{"_type":"span","marks":[],"text":", all members of Scott's South Pole expedition died fewer than 18 kilometers (11 miles) from a resupply depot.\n\nAmerican explorer Richard E. Byrd became the first person to fly over the South Pole, in 1926, and the Amundsen–Scott South Pole Station was established 30 years later.\n\nHowever, the next ","_key":"f6ba1a597c96"},{"_type":"span","marks":["em"],"text":"overland","_key":"013e6fbb88793"},{"_type":"span","marks":[],"text":" expedition to the South Pole was not made until 1958, more than 40 years after Amundsen and Scott's deadly race. The 1958 expedition was led by legendary New Zealand mountaineer Sir Edmund Hillary, who had become the first person to scale Mount Everest in 1953.\n\n","_key":"013e6fbb88794"},{"_type":"span","marks":["strong"],"text":"Transportation to the South Pole","_key":"013e6fbb88795"},{"_type":"span","marks":[],"text":"\n\nAlmost all scientists and support personnel, as well as supplies, are flown in to the South Pole. Hardy ","_key":"dd153a8eeeff"},{"_type":"span","marks":["062f83c2e449"],"text":"military","_key":"0fb5f4cecc83"},{"_type":"span","marks":[],"text":" aircraft usually fly from McMurdo Station, an American facility on the Antarctic coast and the most populated area on the continent. The extreme and unpredictable weather around the pole can often delay flights.\n\nIn 2009, the U.S. completed construction of the South Pole Traverse. Also called the McMurdo-South Pole Highway, this stretch of unpaved road runs more than 1,600 kilometers (995 miles) over the Antarctic ice sheet, from McMurdo Station to the Amundsen–Scott South Pole Station. It takes about 40 days for supplies to reach the pole from McMurdo, but the route is far more reliable and inexpensive than air flights. The highway can also supply much heavier equipment (such as that needed by the South Pole's astrophysics laboratories) than aircraft.\n\n","_key":"d2134f7a2399"},{"_type":"span","marks":["strong"],"text":"Resources and Territorial Claims","_key":"013e6fbb88797"},{"_type":"span","marks":[],"text":"\n\nThe entire continent of Antarctica has no official political boundaries. Seven countries made defined claims to Antarctic territory prior to the Antarctic Treaty of 1959, which does not legally recognize any claims.\n","_key":"013e6fbb88798"}],"_type":"block","style":"normal","_key":"2321ac24d536"}],"instructionalLinks":null,"collectionItems":null,"video":null,"interactive":null},"keyImage":{"name":"south-pole.jpg","height":743,"access_mode":"public","width":990,"_version":1,"bytes":554647,"_type":"cloudinary.asset","secure_url":"https://images.nationalgeographic.org/image/upload/v1652339615/EducationHub/photos/south-pole.jpg","url":"https://images.nationalgeographic.org/image/upload/v1652339615/EducationHub/photos/south-pole.jpg","resource_type":"image","format":"jpg","context":{"custom":{"alt":"Peaks come through glacier ice","caption":"South Pole"}},"source":{"name":"cloudinary","id":"JTdCJTIyZm9ybWF0JTIyJTNBJTIwJTIyanBnJTIyJTJDJTIwJTIycHVibGljX2lkJTIyJTNBJTIwJTIyRWR1Y2F0aW9uSHViJTJGcGhvdG9zJTJGc291dGgtcG9sZSUyMiUyQyUyMCUyMnJlc291cmNlX3R5cGUlMjIlM0ElMjAlMjJpbWFnZSUyMiUyQyUyMCUyMnR5cGUlMjIlM0ElMjAlMjJ1cGxvYWQlMjIlMkMlMjAlMjJyYXdUcmFuc2Zvcm1hdGlvbiUyMiUzQSUyMG51bGwlN0Q="},"metadata":{"cr